  "body": "NOTE I renamed the prior \"Parameters\" to be Macros. Parameters should actually mean this.\r\n\r\nParameters should be like `public` where in addition to a getter it makes a setter that has a specific access group that can change them, and maybe creates an `event` log that sends when it is changed.\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n```python\r\n@public # Propose alternative syntax for making something public?\r\nowner: address\r\n\r\n@parameter(owner) #Only owner can change maintainer\r\nmaintainer: address\r\n\r\n@parameter(owner, maintainer) # Owner and maintainer can change the fee\r\nfee: currency_value\r\n\r\ndef __init__():\r\n   self.owner = msg.sender\r\n...\r\n```\r\nwhich would produce something like this in the intermediate compilation stage:\r\n```python\r\nowner: address\r\nmaintainer: address\r\nfee: currency_value\r\n\r\n# Because owner is @public\r\n@constant\r\ndef get_owner() -> address:\r\n  return self.owner\r\n\r\n# Because maintainer is @parameter\r\n@constant\r\ndef get_maintainer() -> address:\r\n  return self.maintainer\r\n# Because maintainer is @parameter(owner)\r\ndef set_maintainer(_maintainer: address):\r\n  assert msg.sender == self.owner # access control\r\n  self.maintainer = _maintainer\r\n  # Event log here? e.g. NewMaintainer(_maintainer)\r\n\r\n# Because fee is @parameter\r\n@constant\r\ndef get_fee() -> currency_value:\r\n  return self.fee\r\n# Because fee is @parameter(owner, maintainer)\r\ndef set_fee(_fee: address):\r\n  assert msg.sender == self.owner or msg.sender == self.maintainer # access control\r\n  # alternatively, assert msg.sender in [self.owner, self.maintainer]?\r\n  self.fee = _fee\r\n  # Event log here? e.g. NewFee(_fee)\r\n\r\ndef __init__():\r\n   self.owner = msg.sender\r\n...\r\n```\r\n\r\nParameters are a common pattern, and this would be a very readable, easy way to represent that pattern.\r\n\r\n![puppy](https://i.pinimg.com/originals/10/f2/d5/10f2d59bbc3c977d25edb32507adbc2d.jpg)",
